{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "In this chapter I argue that, unlike many of their English peers, practitioners and advocates of experimental philosophy in seventeenth-century Italy kept natural philosophy sharply distinct from theological and religious concerns.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Negatively, the case of Italian experimental philosophers provides a counterexample to the view that either experimental philosophy or seventeenth-century natural philosophy, as a whole, were fused with theology, driven by theological concerns, or pursued primarily to shed light on God.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Positively, the case of Italian experimental philosophers provides evidence for the claim that experimental philosophy does not bear any intrinsic connection with religion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "On the contrary, as we shall see, certain features of the outlook of experimental philosophy made it easy to pursue it in isolation from theological and religious questions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Whether experimental philosophy was presented as an ally of religion or as distinct from it depends, at least in part, on matters of cultural politics, namely, which rhetorical and argumentative strategies were believed to be the most likely to ensure freedom of research and institutional support for the work of experimental philosophers.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Italian writers echoed their rejection of authority, prejudices, prematurely formed systems and speculations not supported by experience; their admiration of Bacon and Boyle and criticisms of Aristotle and his disciples; their praise of the senses, experience and observations, which provide 'the only path' to advance our knowledge of the natural world; and their view that a new, comprehensive natural history ought to provide a 'solid foundation for natural philosophy'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "However, they did not echo their claims on the connection between experimental philosophy and religion.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "They did not present the practice of natural philosophy as an exercise in the cultivation of Christian virtues.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "They did not state that natural philosophy enables us to know the Creator, increase our devotion, or fight atheism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The natural philosophical works of Italian novatores did not even sketch any arguments from design, even though the inclusion of brief arguments from design at least in the prefaces would have been easy and rather conventional, especially for works of natural history.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "If theological concerns had been driving their natural-philosophical reflections, they could have shown it in a variety of ways.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "They could have arranged for their theological views to be published clandestinely, posthumously, abroad, anonymously, or under a false name.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "None of them did, with only one potential exception: a matter-theoretical and theological essay by Domenico Guglielmini, one of the foremost crystallographers of the seventeenth century.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Finally, if theological concerns had played a significant role in the works of the Italian authors who endorsed experimental philosophy, they would have had a strong incentive to elaborate on at least the theologically orthodox portions of their views.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "This would have helped defuse any suspicions of libertinism and it would have given additional credibility to their occasional professions of faith and willingness to submit to the Church.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The fact that Italian authors did not elaborate even on theologically safe topics provides further reason to believe that they had little interest in theology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "If all this is correct, we can conclude that, pace Funkenstein, the seventeenth-century Italian authors who were sympathetic to experimental philosophy did not see science and theology as the same occupation, nor did they seek to fuse theology with physics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Pace Gaukroger, they did not present their natural philosophy as being driven by Christian themes, but as distinct from matters of faith.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "And, pace Cunningham, they did not employ their natural philosophy as an extended argument for a specific view of God.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "This indicates that neither experimental philosophy nor seventeenth-century natural philosophy as a whole, as such, were theologically driven, and it raises the question of what explains the different attitudes of Italian and English authors on the relation between experimental philosophy and religion.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
